\b 4) Explain how Nginx can handle HTTP requests?\b0\par
\pard\li720\sl240\slmult1 Nginx uses the reactor pattern. The main event loop waits for the OS to signal a readiness\par
event- such that the data is accessible to read from a socket, at which instance it is read into the\par
buffer and processed. A Single thread can serve tens of thousands of simultaneous\par
connections.\par
\pard\sl240\slmult1\b 5) In Nginx how you can prevent processing requests with undefined server names?\b0\par
\pard\li720\sl240\slmult1 A server that just drops the requests can be defined as\par
Server \{\par
listen 80;\par
server_name \ldblquote  \ldblquote  ;\par
return 444;\par
\}\par
Here the server name is kept as an empty string which will match request without the \ldblquote Host\rdblquote  header field, and a special Nginx\rquote s non-standard code 444 is returned that terminates the connection.\par
\pard\sl240\slmult1\b 6) What is the advantage of using a \ldblquote reverse proxy server\rdblquote ?\b0\par
\pard\li720\sl240\slmult1 The reverse proxy server can hide the presence and characteristics of the origin server. It acts as an intermediate between internet cloud and web server. It is good for security reason especially when you are using web hosting services.\par
